    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-06-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-06-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="45"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d45">
                <head>45. Briefing Memorandum From the Assistant Secretary of State for
                    Congressional Relations (<persName corresp="#p_BDJ_1">Bennet</persName>) to
                    Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1">Vance</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d45fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy File,
                        P770103–1995. Limited Official Use. <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                            >Vance</persName>’s initials are stamped on the memorandum.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-06-03">June 3, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="italic">Panama Strategy</hi>
                </p>
                <p>I have been working closely with a White House group, including <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> staff, <persName corresp="#p_MF_2">Frank
                        Moore</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_PJ_1">Jody Powell</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_BL_1">Landon Butler</persName> and sometimes <persName
                        corresp="#p_JH_1">Hamilton Jordan</persName>, on Congressional and public
                    relations strategy for the Panama negotiations.</p>
                <p>In anticipation of press leaks, we began briefings on the Hill last week and will
                    continue in the week ahead. Senator <persName corresp="#p_BHF_1">Byrd</persName>
                    believes the defense provision we have negotiated will make the Treaty much more
                        saleable.<note n="2" xml:id="d45fn2">See <ref target="#d41">Document
                            41</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>We have developed a detailed schedule of tactical steps for selling the Treaty,
                    once the agreement is signed. We consider it critical that the Treaty be
                    submitted to the Senate before the August recess so that (a) Members will have
                    solid arguments in favor of it before they return to their constituencies for
                    the August recess and (b) so the Members can complete action before the 1978
                    election year.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
